        "excerpt": "May God do so to the enemies of David, and more also, if by morning I leave as much as one male of any who belong to him.",
        "body": "The narrator prepares the reader for Nabal's behavior before Nabal speaks — 'the man was harsh and evil in his dealings' (v.3). This pre-characterization is not merely descriptive; it is judicial. When Nabal refuses David's men with contempt, the reader is meant to see it as consistent with who he already is, not as a surprising development. His refusal has three elements: a denial of David's identity ('Who is David?'), a characterization of David as a runaway slave (v.10), and a claim of exclusive ownership over his own provisions ('my bread, my water, my meat,' v.11). The threefold possessive is the voice of the man who has forgotten that the LORD gives and the LORD takes away.\n\nDavid's response is militarily rational and morally catastrophic. Four hundred armed men, a sworn oath of total annihilation by dawn, the explicit self-assessment that he has been returned evil for good (v.21). Each element of David's internal reasoning is technically accurate and spiritually dangerous. He has been wronged. Nabal did return evil for good. His anger is not irrational. But David has moved from 'I have been wronged' to 'I will execute total vengeance' in one emotional step, without a pause for the question Abigail will shortly ask him: what will this cost your future? The same pattern appears in Jonah 4, Elijah under the broom tree (1 Kgs 19:4), and Peter's sword-drawing in Gethsemane — legitimate grievance as the fuel for disproportionate action.\n\nThe oath formula in v.22 is the chapter's darkest moment. 'May God do so to the enemies of David, and more also' is the standard Israelite oath of imprecation (cf. 1 Sam 3:17; 14:44; 2 Sam 3:9) — David invokes divine sanction on his own violent intention. He has confused his personal vendetta with a holy war. Abigail's intercession will need to untangle that confusion before the swords arrive.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ra* (evil) appears six times in the chapter (vv.3, 17, 21, 26, 28, 39) — Nabal's character, the disaster he has created, the wrong David received, and finally the wickedness returned on Nabal's own head. The word traces the chapter's moral arc. *Sheqer* (in vain, v.21) — literally 'for falsehood'; David is saying that his protection of Nabal's property was protection given to a man whose word turned out to be worthless."
