        "title": "David's response — the reception of rebuke as the mark of kingship",
        "range": "25:32-35",
        "excerpt": "Blessed be the LORD God of Israel, who sent you this day to meet me, and blessed be your discernment, and blessed be you, who have kept me this day from bloodshed.",
        "body": "David's response to Abigail's intercession is exegetically as important as the speech itself. He blesses three things in sequence: the LORD God of Israel (v.32), Abigail's discernment (*taam*, v.33), and Abigail herself (v.33). The order is theologically deliberate. He does not first praise Abigail and then remember to credit God — he begins with God and moves to the instrument. He has recognized that Abigail's appearance in that ravine was not coincidence but divine sending: 'who sent you this day to meet me.'\n\nThe acknowledgment in v.34 is the chapter's most searching moment of self-knowledge: 'as the LORD God of Israel lives, who has restrained me from harming you, unless you had come quickly to meet me, surely there would not have been left to Nabal until the morning light as much as one male.' David does not say 'I was patient' or 'I reconsidered.' He says explicitly that without Abigail's interception, the massacre would have happened. He is not claiming the credit for the restraint; he is locating it in divine providence working through a woman's wisdom and speed.\n\nThis is the moment that distinguishes David from Saul. When Samuel rebuked Saul (1 Sam 15:13-23), Saul deflected, rationalized, and ultimately blamed the people. When Abigail rebukes David, he receives the rebuke, credits God, and calls her wisdom blessed. The capacity to receive correction without deflection is the mark of the covenant king — and the absence of that capacity was the final diagnosis of Saul's rejection. Jonathan Edwards noted that the evidence of genuine humility is not merely a low self-opinion but the willingness to hear truth from the mouth of someone you did not expect and to act on it without resentment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Taam* (discernment, v.33) — literally 'taste,' the capacity to perceive what is fitting, to distinguish what is right from what merely feels urgent. It is the word wisdom literature uses for the discernment that reads a situation correctly (cf. Prov 11:22). David is blessing not merely Abigail's intelligence but her specific faculty of moral perception."
