        "excerpt": "About ten days later, the LORD struck Nabal and he died. When David heard that Nabal was dead, he said, 'Blessed be the LORD, who has pleaded the cause of my reproach from the hand of Nabal and has kept back His servant from evil.'",
        "body": "The account of Nabal's death is structured to prevent any natural explanation. Abigail returns home to find Nabal feasting like a king, drunk and oblivious (v.36) — the man who refused hospitality to David is providing hospitality to himself on a royal scale, the bitter irony sharpened by the word *mishteh* ('feast' — the same festive context David's men had named in their request, v.8). Abigail waits until morning, tells him everything, and 'his heart died within him so that he became as a stone' (v.37). Ten days later, the LORD struck him and he died (v.38).\n\nThe ten-day interval is the narrator's theological precision. Strokes can be immediately fatal or can proceed in stages; what the narrator will not allow the reader to infer is that Nabal's death was simply the psychosomatic shock of bad news delivered after a heavy night of drinking. The LORD struck him. The same verb (*nagaph*) is used of God's judicial strikes in Exodus 12:23 (the Passover), Numbers 14:37 (the spies who brought the bad report), and 2 Samuel 12:15 (the child born of David and Bathsheba). The word is not clinical; it is judicial.\n\nDavid's response is a doxology that simultaneously recognizes three things: the LORD has acted as his advocate (*riv*, he has pleaded David's cause — the legal vocabulary of covenant lawsuit); the LORD has kept David's own hand clean; and the LORD has returned Nabal's evil on Nabal's own head. The threefold recognition is the chapter's theological summary. Vengeance belongs to God (Deut 32:35; Romans 12:19). Not because the offense is minor, but because God's execution of justice is both perfectly timed and perfectly calibrated — it falls on the offender without creating additional innocent casualties. Douglas Moo's comment on Romans 12:19 applies precisely here: 'leaving room for God's wrath' is not passivity but active trust that the righteous Judge will act, and that His action will not require the believer to compromise their own integrity to secure it."
