        "body": "The chapter closes with a brief, dense paragraph that is more dynastic notation than romantic narrative. David's proposal to Abigail follows immediately upon his benediction over the LORD's vindication — the woman who saved his conscience becomes part of the household she told him God was building. Her acceptance is characteristically humble: she bows to the ground and calls herself 'a maid to wash the feet of my lord's servants' (v.41). The foot-washing image is the ancient Near Eastern posture of radical lowliness — not false modesty but genuine self-positioning under another's authority.\n\nThe two additional editorial notes — Ahinoam of Jezreel (v.43) and the theft of Michal by Saul's reassignment to Palti (v.44) — are not incidental. The narrator is tracking the formation and disruption of David's household as a dynastic matter. Saul's act of giving Michal to Palti (cf. 1 Sam 18:27; 2 Sam 3:14-16) is both politically hostile and legally transgressive — it is Saul once more acting as if the covenant promises that apply to David do not apply. The chapter that began with Samuel's death ends with Saul's continued erosion of David's legitimate claims, even as God is simultaneously building the house Saul is trying to dismantle.\n\nRead canonically, the marriage to Abigail is one of the chapter's most understated proofs of Abigail's theological claim. She told David in v.31 that when the LORD deals well with him, he should remember her. The chapter ends with David remembering her — not as the woman who rebuked him, but as the woman whose wisdom saved him, and whom the LORD brought into his life as part of the covenant provision she herself had prophesied.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Berakhah* (gift, v.27) — the same word as blessing; Abigail's provisions are not merely food but a *berakhah*, a covenant blessing offered in the name of the LORD. *Nagid* (ruler, v.30) — the technical term for Israel's appointed leader; used of Saul at his appointment (1 Sam 9:16) and now applied to David by Abigail before any public enthronement. She speaks the prophetic vocabulary of kingship over a man still sleeping in the wilderness."
